  <title>How to actually pick between HVAC quotes</title>
</head>
<body style="margin:0;padding:0;background-color:#ffffff;font-family:-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,'Segoe UI',Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;color:#27272a;">
  <div style="max-width:600px;margin:0 auto;padding:32px 20px;">

    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">Hey,</p>

    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">
      You've now had 10 days with your HVAC quotes. Day 0: how to score them. Day 3: the pricing tricks to spot. Today: the actual decision.
    </p>

    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 24px 0;">
      If you've done the work, your quotes have been filtered. Either you're left with 2-3 clean ones that hit the 10-item checklist and don't show any of the pricing tricks, OR one of your originals dropped out (it was the brand-swap one, or the cash-deal one, or the missing-permit one). Either way, the next move is choosing.
    </p>

    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">
      Here's the framework. Score each remaining quote on five dimensions, then use the scores to decide. The tiebreaker, when scores are within 5%: <em>don't pick on price.</em>
    </p>

    <h2 style="font-size:17px;color:#18181b;margin:32px 0 12px 0;">The five dimensions:</h2>

    <!-- Dimension 1 -->
    <h3 style="font-size:16px;color:#18181b;margin:24px 0 8px 0;">1. Price.</h3>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">
      Total bottom-line, including permit, equipment, labor, disposal. Use the cheapest as your baseline (call it 1.00x), and compute how much more expensive each other quote is. If the cheapest is $12,000 and another is $13,500, the second is 1.125x &mdash; 12.5% more expensive.
    </p>

    <!-- Dimension 2 -->
    <h3 style="font-size:16px;color:#18181b;margin:24px 0 8px 0;">2. Warranty.</h3>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">
      Both <strong>parts AND labor warranties, separately.</strong> The standard baseline is 10 years parts / 2 years labor. A 12/5 quote (12-year parts, 5-year labor) is meaningfully better. A 10/1 or 10/0 is meaningfully worse &mdash; labor warranty is the one that costs you real money if something fails.
    </p>

    <!-- Dimension 3 -->
    <h3 style="font-size:16px;color:#18181b;margin:24px 0 8px 0;">3. Contractor reputation.</h3>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 12px 0;">
      Three places to check, in rough order of usefulness:
    </p>
    <ul style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 16px 24px;padding:0;">
      <li style="margin-bottom:10px;"><strong>State contractor license lookup</strong> (free, definitive). Confirms the license is current, scope covers HVAC, insurance is on file, and surfaces any disciplinary actions or formal complaints. Search &ldquo;[your state] contractor license search&rdquo; &mdash; every state has one. This is the source that actually has consequences attached to it.</li>
      <li style="margin-bottom:10px;"><strong>BBB</strong> (bbb.org). Useful for spotting <em>patterns</em> of unresolved complaints, not as a single letter-grade verdict (the grade is partly pay-for-play). Look at: total complaint count for a contractor of this size, percentage marked resolved, and whether the contractor responded at all. Five resolved complaints is fine; two unresolved-and-unanswered is a signal.</li>
      <li><strong>Google reviews and hyper-local platforms</strong> (Nextdoor, neighborhood Facebook groups). Noisier than the first two but catches recent issues the BBB misses by months. Filter for reviews from your ZIP code or surrounding ZIPs if possible &mdash; an installer who's beloved across town can still be terrible at your specific build type.</li>
    </ul>

    <!-- Dimension 4 -->
    <h3 style="font-size:16px;color:#18181b;margin:24px 0 8px 0;">4. Timeline.</h3>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">
      When can they install, and how long does the install take? A contractor who can do it next week may be available because they're not in demand. A contractor who's a month out is often busy because they're good. Not always &mdash; but it's a directional signal worth weighing.
    </p>

    <!-- Dimension 5 -->
    <h3 style="font-size:16px;color:#18181b;margin:24px 0 8px 0;">5. What's included.</h3>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">
      From the Day 0 checklist: did they include commissioning? Old-system disposal? Electrical work? Full ductwork? Each &ldquo;yes&rdquo; is included scope. The cheapest quote isn't a bargain if it's missing $2,000 worth of scope the other quotes include.
    </p>

    <h2 style="font-size:17px;color:#18181b;margin:32px 0 12px 0;">A worked example:</h2>

    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 12px 0;">Three quotes from the same evaluation:</p>
    <ul style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 16px 24px;padding:0;">
      <li style="margin-bottom:8px;"><strong>Quote A:</strong> $11,500. 10-year parts / 1-year labor. Mixed BBB record. Available next week. Missing commissioning and disposal line items.</li>
      <li style="margin-bottom:8px;"><strong>Quote B:</strong> $13,200. 10-year parts / 5-year labor. A+ BBB, no complaints. 3 weeks out. Includes everything.</li>
      <li><strong>Quote C:</strong> $12,400. 10-year parts / 2-year labor. Solid BBB, one resolved complaint. 2 weeks out. Includes everything except commissioning.</li>
    </ul>

    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 12px 0;">
      On price alone, A wins by $1,700 over C and $1,900 over B. But:
    </p>
    <ul style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 16px 24px;padding:0;">
      <li style="margin-bottom:10px;"><strong>Quote A is missing scope, not winning on price.</strong> No commissioning (~$300 if added later), no old-system disposal (~$200), and a 1-year labor warranty vs. the others' 2-5. True apples-to-apples cost is closer to $13,000 once you backfill the missing items &mdash; barely cheaper than C, more expensive than B once warranty value is priced in.</li>
      <li style="margin-bottom:10px;"><strong>Quote B's 5-year labor warranty is worth ~$2,000 in expected value.</strong> The compressor or heat exchanger failing in years 3-5 is the most common expensive failure mode. Quote A leaves you holding $1,500-2,500 in labor for that repair; Quote B covers it. That gap alone closes the $1,700 price difference between A and B.</li>
      <li><strong>Quote B being 3 weeks out tells you something good.</strong> Contractors with 2-3 week wait lists are usually busy because they're good. Quote A's &ldquo;available next week&rdquo; sometimes means new in business &mdash; but in established markets it more often means slack capacity from lost customers. Not a hard rule, but a directional tiebreaker that points the same direction as the warranty math.</li>
    </ul>

    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 24px 0;">
      The right answer here is <strong>B</strong> &mdash; even though it's the most expensive on paper. The 5-year labor warranty alone is worth roughly $2,000 in expected service costs over the system's lifetime.
    </p>

    <h2 style="font-size:17px;color:#18181b;margin:32px 0 12px 0;">The tiebreaker:</h2>

    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 24px 0;">
      When two quotes are within 5% on price (so within ~$600 on a $12,000 install), <strong>don't pick on price.</strong> Pick on warranty + timeline + reputation. The price difference will round to nothing over a 15-year system lifespan; the warranty + reputation difference compounds.
    </p>

    <h2 style="font-size:17px;color:#18181b;margin:32px 0 12px 0;">The &ldquo;still unsure&rdquo; play:</h2>

    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">
      If you're still genuinely torn between two quotes &mdash; or if all your quotes are missing pieces that would make the decision clean &mdash; the asymmetric move is one more independent bid from a contractor who hits all 10 items on the Day 0 checklist. Takes 24 hours. Cost is one phone call. The upside is either confirmation that your existing favorite is the right call, or a third option that's better than both.
    </p>

    <div style="margin:0 0 24px 0;text-align:center;">
